   =20
 =20
Back in 2019  I proposed the Money Stuff S&P ESG Fund, =E2=80=9Ca mutual fu=
nd whose stated mission would be to invest in the 500 companies in the S&P =
500 index with the best environmental, social and governance ratings judged=
 by my proprietary rating system.=E2=80=9D Because there are 500 companies =
in the S&P 500 index, the details of my rating system would not matter very=
 much; all of the companies in the S&P 500 would get in, and the fund would=
 exactly track the index.[1] The fund would just be an S&P 500 index fund. =
But it would have =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D in its name. This, I argued, would =
be good:=09People want exposure to the S&P 500 index with minimal tracking =
error. My fund would have lower tracking error than other ESG funds that us=
e ESG criteria to pick stocks.=09People want low fees. ESG ratings systems =
can be expensive to implement, requiring detailed data and teams of analyst=
s; my ratings system could be cheap to implement because, again, it would n=
ot actually do anything.=C2=A0=09People like to invest in funds that have =
=E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D in the name, and my fund, unlike other S&P 500 index =
funds, would have =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D in the name.Since I wrote that, ESG=
 investing has become an even bigger and more important industry. There hav=
e been various backlashes. One sort of backlash is along the lines of: No, =
ESG is bad. (And so various  US politicians try to make it illegal for inve=
stors to consider environmental or social impact in making investments, etc=
.)Another sort of backlash is along the lines of: Sure, ESG is good, but ES=
G=C2=A0as practiced is often fake. The theory here is that=C2=A0people who =
call themselves investment managers=C2=A0do not=C2=A0really=C2=A0care about=
 ESG factors, and ESG is a marketing term rather than a real commitment. Li=
ke me with my fake ESG fund, the theory goes, these=C2=A0managers=C2=A0unde=
rstand that there is a demand for funds with =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D in the n=
ame (and in the marketing materials), and they seek to satisfy that demand =
at the lowest possible cost, by slapping the name =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D on =
a fund without making much effort to police companies=E2=80=99 environmenta=
l, social and governance behavior.=C2=A0They are =E2=80=9Cgreenwashing,=E2=
=80=9D pretending to care about ESG in their marketing materials without re=
ally doing anything about it.This theory leads to a diffuse set of complain=
ts in part because ESG is a diffuse set of strategies: Any ESG fund will ha=
ve to make trade-offs between, you know, E and S, or whatever; it will have=
 to decide whether to buy shares in an electric car company that exploits w=
orkers or an oil company with a really diverse board of directors. If you d=
isagree with a fund=E2=80=99s=C2=A0trade-offs, or its ranking system, you c=
an always say =E2=80=9Cthis isn=E2=80=99t real ESG, this is greenwashing.=
=E2=80=9D To some extent ESG means =E2=80=9Cbuy companies that you think ar=
e making the world better,=E2=80=9D and if different people have different =
conceptions of what makes the world better then they will disagree about wh=
at ESG demands.For a while now there have been rumors that the US Securitie=
s and Exchange Commission will be cracking down on fake ESG practices; SEC =
Chair Gary Gensler  has warned that probes were coming. You could imagine a=
 range of possible complaints here. One might be:=C2=A0An ESG fund makes ES=
G choices and the SEC disagrees with them. =E2=80=9CYou said you were ESG,=
=E2=80=9D the SEC might say, =E2=80=9Cbut you were overweight oil companies=
 and underweight solar companies, and a real ESG fund would never buy oil c=
ompanies, so you are doing fraud.=E2=80=9D I think that this sort of thing =
is what a lot of people want, a true substantive policing of ESG claims, bu=
t it is very tricky. You might have a list of things that ESG funds should =
and shouldn=E2=80=99t do, but how do you know that the SEC will have the sa=
me list? How do you know that your list, or the SEC=E2=80=99s, is right?=C2=
=A0I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s absolutely impossible for the SEC to =
impose substantive=C2=A0restrictions on what it means to be an ESG fund, bu=
t it would be tough, and a huge extension of the SEC=E2=80=99s job.[2]An ea=
sier and more plausible sort of case would be like: An ESG fund makes its E=
SG choices for non-ESG reasons, and has lots of emails and chat transcripts=
 to that effect. Somewhere on the fund=E2=80=99s servers there is an email =
from a portfolio manager to its environmental analyst saying, like, =E2=80=
=9CThis company is a hideous polluter and would never meet the ESG standard=
s that we publish and that we use to attract investors, but the stock keeps=
 going up, can we ignore our standards so I can buy it,=E2=80=9D and the an=
alyst replies =E2=80=9Csure, our bonuses are more important than ESG, I=E2=
=80=99ll just write a fake report saying it=E2=80=99s good,=E2=80=9D and th=
e portfolio manager replies =E2=80=9Cgreat, hope our investors don=E2=80=99=
t find out about this ESG fraud we=E2=80=99re doing,=E2=80=9D and the analy=
st replies =E2=80=9Clolololol or the SEC, see you in jail!=E2=80=9D And the=
n the SEC finds that email and prints it in a complaint and the fund settle=
s for $100 million.Here the point is not that the SEC is telling the fund=
=C2=A0what ESG means.=C2=A0Here the=C2=A0fund=C2=A0has said what ESG means =
to it =E2=80=94=C2=A0it has disclosed some set of procedures and criteria f=
or ESG, and used those procedures and criteria to=C2=A0market itself to inv=
estors who care about ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0but secretly it was lying and igno=
ring those procedures and criteria, either to pursue non-ESG goals or just =
out of laziness. This is much more in the SEC=E2=80=99s wheelhouse. This is=
 just =E2=80=9Cyou said you were doing one thing, but you did another thing=
, and we have documentary evidence, so pay a fine.=E2=80=9DHere=E2=80=99s a=
 case from today=C2=A0that is like that, only boring:The Securities and Exc=
hange Commission today charged BNY Mellon Investment Adviser, Inc. for miss=
tatements and omissions about Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) c=
onsiderations in making investment decisions for certain mutual funds that =
it managed. To settle the charges, BNY Mellon Investment Adviser agreed to =
pay a $1.5 million penalty.The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that, from July 20=
18 to September 2021, BNY Mellon Investment Adviser represented or implied =
in various statements that all investments in the funds had undergone an ES=
G quality review, even though that was not always the case. The order finds=
 that numerous investments held by certain funds did not have an ESG qualit=
y review score as of the time of investment.BNY Mellon has an affiliate cal=
led Newton Investment Management that runs some of its mutual funds. Some o=
f those funds are ESG funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0the SEC calls them =E2=80=9CSust=
ainable Funds=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=C2=A0for those funds, a Responsib=
le Investing Team reviews every investment and gives it an ESG rating from =
1 to 10. The SEC complaint =E2=80=A6 does not quite say that the Sustainabl=
e Funds only invest in stocks and bonds with high ESG ratings? I assume tha=
t the funds give=C2=A0some=C2=A0preference to high ESG ratings but I really=
 don=E2=80=99t know. That=E2=80=99s not the point here, though, and the SEC=
 actually has no complaints about the Sustainable Funds.But Newton also run=
s some other BNY Mellon funds that are not ESG funds; the SEC calls them =
=E2=80=9COverlay Funds,=E2=80=9D and they have non-ESG-y names like =E2=80=
=9CBNY Mellon Global Equity Income Fund=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CBNY Mellon Gl=
obal Emerging Markets Fund=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CBNY Mellon Global Dynamic =
Bond Income Fund.=E2=80=9D Nonetheless they are a little ESG-y. BNY Mellon =
would tell investors that they considered ESG issues. From the Overlay Fund=
s=E2=80=99 prospectuses:Integrated into the investment process, [the Sub-Ad=
viser] has a well-established approach to responsible investment. This proc=
ess includes identifying and considering the Environmental, Social and Gove=
rnance (ESG) risks, opportunities and issues throughout the research proces=
s via [the Sub-Adviser=E2=80=99s] proprietary quality reviews, in an effort=
 to ensure that any material ESG issues are considered.=C2=A0And when BNY M=
ellon got requests for proposals from other investment firms, it described =
the funds as considering ESG stuff:During the Relevant Period, BNYMIA prepa=
red RFP Responses to other investment firms that were evaluating the Overla=
y Funds for their own clients. In response to numerous inquiries regarding =
ESG considerations, BNYMIA included language that described the Sub-Adviser=
=E2=80=99s Responsible Investment Team=E2=80=99s research process, includin=
g its preparation of ESG quality reviews. BNYMIA provided RFP Responses whi=
ch stated that the Sub-Adviser=E2=80=99s Responsible Investment Team prepar=
ed an ESG quality review for every security recommended by the Sub-Adviser=
=E2=80=99s analysts. For example, BNYMIA stated in an RFP Response that =E2=
=80=9CESG considerations are taken into account at every stage of the inves=
tment process=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cahead of investing, each security being=
 considered for investment by our global industry analysts must have an ESG=
 quality review conducted by a member of [the Responsible Investment Team].=
=E2=80=9DHere there are=C2=A0absolutely no substantive claims=C2=A0about ho=
w BNY Mellon takes these factors into account. =E2=80=9CWe review every inv=
estment for ESG quality and then buy whichever stocks we think will go up,=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhichever stocks have the highest dividend yields,=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhichever stocks are in the index,=E2=80=9D would all be=
 consistent with what these statements actually say. Or =E2=80=9Cbefore we =
invest, our responsible investment team writes a report on the stock, which=
 we then throw away before anyone can read it.=E2=80=9D There is nothing he=
re that gives the SEC a hook to sue BNY Mellon on a theory like =E2=80=9Cyo=
u said you cared about ESG but actually you prioritized economics over ESG.=
=E2=80=9D The only claims here are that BNY Mellon considered=C2=A0ESG fact=
ors, not that it did anything specific about them.However! Apparently it di=
d not=C2=A0always=C2=A0consider those factors.=C2=A0The=C2=A0Overlay Funds =
would sometimes buy stocks and bonds without an=C2=A0ESG review:Numerous eq=
uity and/or corporate bond investments held by certain Overlay Funds did no=
t have an ESG quality review score as of the time of investment. For exampl=
e, out of 185 investments made by one Overlay Fund between January 1, 2019 =
and March 31, 2021, 67 did not have an ESG quality review score as of the t=
ime of investment (or, in the case of corporate bonds, within 30 days after=
 purchase, consistent with the Sub-Adviser=E2=80=99s policy), amounting to =
nearly 25 percent of the fund=E2=80=99s net assets as of March 31, 2021.=C2=
=A0So =E2=80=A6=C2=A0this is BNY Mellon selling=C2=A0non-ESG funds with mar=
keting materials that say =E2=80=9Cwe consider ESG for every investment,=E2=
=80=9D but in fact they only considered ESG for like 75% of their investmen=
ts. They said they always wrote reports, but sometimes they did not write r=
eports. Fraud!I suppose that this could be the first case in a wave of SEC =
ESG enforcement actions, but I want to emphasize how limited it is, and how=
 inevitable those limits are.=C2=A0In general, the marketing pitch for an E=
SG fund will be[3]:=09We consider a range of environmental, social and gove=
rnance factors that we think matter, and balance those factors against each=
 other subjectively to produce some sort of explicit or implicit ESG score.=
=09Then we consider the ESG score along with traditional=C2=A0research on t=
he stock=E2=80=99s fundamental value, and balance our valuation view with o=
ur ESG view to decide what stocks to buy.If you want, you can probably find=
 things to object to in the way any ESG fund does either of these weighting=
s. You can probably find some funds that do these weightings in ways that y=
ou find outrageous and cavalier and destructive and even dishonest. But it =
is hard for the SEC to do that without=C2=A0proof=C2=A0that the fund is bei=
ng=C2=A0knowingly=C2=A0dishonest. If a fund writes an ESG report, it=E2=80=
=99s hard for the SEC to say =E2=80=9Cyour ESG report wasn=E2=80=99t good e=
nough,=E2=80=9D or even =E2=80=9Cyou did not give enough weight to your ESG=
 reports in choosing which stocks to buy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But if it doesn=E2=
=80=99t write the report at all, sure, that=E2=80=99s a problem.The lesson =
here is that, if you say you have an ESG process for all of your investment=
s, then you have to have an ESG process for all of your investments. There =
are no lessons about what that process has to look like.
