      Backed stablecoin?
   =20
 =20
We talked recently=C2=A0about the possibility of contagion from the cryptoc=
urrency markets to the broader financial system. My basic view is that=C2=
=A0there's not much, really, but there=E2=80=99s more than there used to be=
, and it will be a good sign for crypto if there=C2=A0is=C2=A0more contagio=
n. If crypto is more tied up with traditional finance =E2=80=94=C2=A0if mor=
e investors own both bonds and crypto, if crypto provides financing for tra=
ditional businesses, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that will be a sign that cryp=
to is=C2=A0important, but it will also increase the risks of crypto.One pop=
ular theory of contagion is about stablecoins. Not algorithmic stablecoins,=
 which try to be worth a dollar without holding any dollars, and which can =
crash to zero with surprisingly little impact on anything else, but =E2=80=
=9Cbacked=E2=80=9D stablecoins like Tether and USD Coin, which try to be wo=
rth a dollar by holding roughly $1 of dollar-denominated financial assets (=
commercial paper, Treasuries, bank deposits, etc.) for each $1 of stablecoi=
ns they issue. If there is a run on one of those stablecoins, then they wil=
l need to sell their underlying assets, which, if the coins are=C2=A0big=C2=
=A0enough, could cause the prices of those assets to go down.When we discus=
sed this,  I wrote that =E2=80=9Cat a high level you could argue that Tethe=
r is one of the more important crypto projects in terms of having an effect=
 on the real economy,=E2=80=9D just because it purportedly buys so much com=
mercial paper, meaning that it effectively lends billions of dollars to (pr=
esumably=C2=A0non-crypto)=C2=A0companies to fund their operations. On the o=
ther hand, lots of people have their doubts about Tether, in part because i=
t bizarrely refuses to disclose much about its holdings, and because there =
is curiously little evidence about what Tether =E2=80=94=C2=A0which seems t=
o be one of the world=E2=80=99s biggest buyers of commercial paper =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0actually buys.In that vein, here is a new paper by Sang Rae Kim at=
 Yale on =E2=80=9CHow the Cryptocurrency Market is Connected to the Financi=
al Market=E2=80=9D:The cryptocurrency market is connected to the traditiona=
l financial market through reserve-backed stablecoins. A one standard devia=
tion ($320 million) increase in the issuance of major stablecoins (Tether a=
nd USD Coin) on a given day results in a 10.7% increase in the commercial p=
aper issuance quantity, a 20 basis point decrease in the commercial paper y=
ield, and a 15 basis point decrease in the Treasury yield the following day=
. This shows that the exponential growth of stablecoins created an excess d=
emand for short-term money-like safe assets such as commercial paper and Tr=
easury. I also explore the fiat cryptocurrency market's effect on the comme=
rcial paper market. A one standard deviation increase in the market capital=
ization growth of major fiat cryptocurrencies (Bitcoin, Binance Coin, and E=
thereum) on a given day results in an 11.9% decrease in the commercial pape=
r issuance quantity, a 20 basis point increase in the commercial paper yiel=
d, and a 18 basis point increase in the Treasury yield the following day. T=
his result suggests that investors exchange stablecoins for fiat cryptocurr=
ency when the fiat cryptocurrency market is doing well, lowering the demand=
 for stablecoins and thus commercial paper.Huh! A correlation between stabl=
ecoin issuance and commercial-paper issuance does suggest that, you know, t=
he stablecoins hold commercial paper. Kim also =E2=80=9Cconduct[ed]=C2=A0an=
 event study that studies the impact of Tether=E2=80=99s shift in their res=
erve management strategy away from holding commercial paper to holding Trea=
suries,=E2=80=9D finding that =E2=80=9Cstablecoin issuers=E2=80=99 impact o=
n the commercial paper market was significantly subdued following this stra=
tegy shift,=E2=80=9D suggesting that the=C2=A0strategy shift was real.On th=
e other hand a=C2=A015 basis point=C2=A0effect on US Treasury yields=C2=A0s=
eems like it might prove too much? Treasuries trade more than half a trilli=
on dollars a day, and I don=E2=80=99t really believe that the demand=C2=A0f=
or Tether has a big effect on the demand for Treasuries. (There may be some=
=C2=A0correlation:=C2=A0A flight to safety in crypto markets might mean mor=
e demand for stablecoins, while=C2=A0a flight to safety in traditional mark=
ets might mean more demand for Treasuries.) I guess when demand for stablec=
oins drives demand for US Treasuries, that=E2=80=99s when you=E2=80=99ll kn=
ow that crypto has really arrived.
