<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">ESG</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in 2019 <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27811549.267618/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTEtMTEvZXNnLXN0b2Nrcy1hcmUtZ3JhZGVkLW=
9uLWEtY3VydmU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUyMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1d=
G1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0=
dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1696dd55" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I proposed</a> the Money S=
tuff S&amp;P ESG Fund, =E2=80=9Ca mutual fund whose stated mission would be=
 to invest in the 500 companies in the S&amp;P 500 index with the best envi=
ronmental, social and governance ratings judged by my proprietary rating sy=
stem.=E2=80=9D Because there are 500 companies in the S&amp;P 500 index, th=
e details of my rating system would not matter very much; all of the compan=
ies in the S&amp;P 500 would get in, and the fund would exactly track the i=
ndex.[1] The fund would just be an S&amp;P 500 index fund. But it would hav=
e =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D in its name. This, I argued, would be good:</p><ol =
style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People want exposure to the S&amp;P 500 i=
ndex with minimal tracking error. My fund would have lower tracking error t=
han other ESG funds that use ESG criteria to pick stocks.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People want low fees. ESG ratings systems can be e=
xpensive to implement, requiring detailed data and teams of analysts; my ra=
tings system could be cheap to implement because, again, it would not actua=
lly do anything.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People like=
 to invest in funds that have =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D in the name, and my fun=
d, unlike other S&amp;P 500 index funds, would have =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D i=
n the name.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since I wrote that, ESG i=
nvesting has become an even bigger and more important industry. There have =
been various backlashes. One sort of backlash is along the lines of: No, ES=
G is bad. (And so various <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/27811549.267618/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjItMDUtMjAvd2h5LWVzZy1pbnZlc3RpbmctaXMtdW5kZXItcmVwdWJsaWNhbi1hdHRhY2=
s_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUyMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB18decf9c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> US politicians</a> try to make it ille=
gal for investors to consider environmental or social impact in making inve=
stments, etc.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another sort of backlash is =
along the lines of: Sure, ESG is good, but ESG=C2=A0<em>as practiced</em> i=
s often fake. The theory here is that=C2=A0people who call themselves inves=
tment managers=C2=A0do not=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>care about ESG factors=
, and ESG is a marketing term rather than a real commitment. Like me with m=
y fake ESG fund, the theory goes, these=C2=A0managers=C2=A0understand that =
there is a demand for funds with =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D in the name (and in =
the marketing materials), and they seek to satisfy that demand at the lowes=
t possible cost, by slapping the name =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D on a fund witho=
ut making much effort to police companies=E2=80=99 environmental, social an=
d governance behavior.=C2=A0They are =E2=80=9Cgreenwashing,=E2=80=9D preten=
ding to care about ESG in their marketing materials without really doing an=
ything about it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This theory leads to a dif=
fuse set of complaints in part because ESG is a diffuse set of strategies: =
Any ESG fund will have to make trade-offs between, you know, E and S, or wh=
atever; it will have to decide whether to buy shares in an electric car com=
pany that exploits workers or an oil company with a really diverse board of=
 directors. If you disagree with a fund=E2=80=99s=C2=A0trade-offs, or its r=
anking system, you can always say =E2=80=9Cthis isn=E2=80=99t real ESG, thi=
s is greenwashing.=E2=80=9D To some extent ESG means =E2=80=9Cbuy companies=
 that you think are making the world better,=E2=80=9D and if different peop=
le have different conceptions of what makes the world better then they will=
 disagree about what ESG demands.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a whi=
le now there have been rumors that the US Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n will be cracking down on fake ESG practices; SEC Chair Gary Gensler <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27811549.267618/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDIvZ2Vuc2xlci1vcm=
RlcnMtc2VjLXRvLXJldmlldy1mdW5kcy1lc2ctZGlzY2xvc3VyZS1wcmFjdGljZXM_Y21waWQ9Q=
kJEMDUyMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0=
ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cBb7f48438" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> has warned</a> that probes were coming. You could=
 imagine a range of possible complaints here. One might be:=C2=A0An ESG fun=
d makes ESG choices and the SEC disagrees with them. =E2=80=9CYou said you =
were ESG,=E2=80=9D the SEC might say, =E2=80=9Cbut you were overweight oil =
companies and underweight solar companies, and a real ESG fund would never =
buy oil companies, so you are doing fraud.=E2=80=9D I think that this sort =
of thing is what a lot of people <em>want</em>, a true substantive policing=
 of ESG claims, but it is very tricky. You might have a list of things that=
 ESG funds should and shouldn=E2=80=99t do, but how do you know that the SE=
C will have the same list? How do you know that your list, or the SEC=E2=80=
=99s, is right?=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s absolutely impossib=
le for the SEC to impose substantive<em>=C2=A0</em>restrictions on what it =
means to be an ESG fund, but it would be tough, and a huge extension of the=
 SEC=E2=80=99s job.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An easier and more p=
lausible sort of case would be like: An ESG fund makes its ESG choices for =
non-ESG reasons, and has lots of emails and chat transcripts to that effect=
. Somewhere on the fund=E2=80=99s servers there is an email from a portfoli=
o manager to its environmental analyst saying, like, =E2=80=9CThis company =
is a hideous polluter and would never meet the ESG standards that we publis=
h and that we use to attract investors, but the stock keeps going up, can w=
e ignore our standards so I can buy it,=E2=80=9D and the analyst replies =
=E2=80=9Csure, our bonuses are more important than ESG, I=E2=80=99ll just w=
rite a fake report saying it=E2=80=99s good,=E2=80=9D and the portfolio man=
ager replies =E2=80=9Cgreat, hope our investors don=E2=80=99t find out abou=
t this ESG fraud we=E2=80=99re doing,=E2=80=9D and the analyst replies =E2=
=80=9Clolololol or the SEC, see you in jail!=E2=80=9D And then the SEC find=
s that email and prints it in a complaint and the fund settles for $100 mil=
lion.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here the point is not that the SEC is=
 telling the fund=C2=A0<em>what ESG means.</em>=C2=A0Here the=C2=A0<em>fund=
=C2=A0</em>has said what ESG means <em>to it </em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0it has dis=
closed some set of procedures and criteria for ESG, and used those procedur=
es and criteria to=C2=A0market itself to investors who care about ESG =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but secretly it was lying and ignoring those procedures and cri=
teria, either to pursue non-ESG goals or just out of laziness. This is much=
 more in the SEC=E2=80=99s wheelhouse. This is just =E2=80=9Cyou said you w=
ere doing one thing, but you did another thing, and we have documentary evi=
dence, so pay a fine.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=
=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27811549.2676=
18/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi04Ng/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB8e28952f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a case from today</a>=C2=A0that is like t=
hat, only boring:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securitie=
s and Exchange Commission today charged BNY Mellon Investment Adviser, Inc.=
 for misstatements and omissions about Environmental, Social, and Governanc=
e (ESG) considerations in making investment decisions for certain mutual fu=
nds that it managed. To settle the charges, BNY Mellon Investment Adviser a=
greed to pay a $1.5 million penalty.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SE=
C=E2=80=99s order finds that, from July 2018 to September 2021, BNY Mellon =
Investment Adviser represented or implied in various statements that all in=
vestments in the funds had undergone an ESG quality review, even though tha=
t was not always the case. The order finds that numerous investments held b=
y certain funds did not have an ESG quality review score as of the time of =
investment.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BNY Mellon has an =
affiliate called Newton Investment Management that runs some of its mutual =
funds. Some of those funds are ESG funds =E2=80=94=C2=A0the SEC calls them =
=E2=80=9CSustainable Funds=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=C2=A0for those funds=
, a Responsible Investing Team reviews every investment and gives it an ESG=
 rating from 1 to 10. The SEC complaint =E2=80=A6 does not quite say that t=
he Sustainable Funds only invest in stocks and bonds with high ESG ratings?=
 I assume that the funds give=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>preference to high ES=
G ratings but I really don=E2=80=99t know. That=E2=80=99s not the point her=
e, though, and the SEC actually has no complaints about the Sustainable Fun=
ds.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Newton also runs some other BNY Mel=
lon funds that are <em>not</em> ESG funds; the SEC calls them =E2=80=9COver=
lay Funds,=E2=80=9D and they have non-ESG-y names like =E2=80=9CBNY Mellon =
Global Equity Income Fund=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CBNY Mellon Global Emerging =
Markets Fund=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CBNY Mellon Global Dynamic Bond Income Fu=
nd.=E2=80=9D Nonetheless they are a <em>little</em> ESG-y. BNY Mellon would=
 tell investors that they considered ESG issues. From the Overlay Funds=E2=
=80=99 prospectuses:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Integrated=
 into the investment process, [the Sub-Adviser] has a well-established appr=
oach to responsible investment. This process includes identifying and consi=
dering the Environmental, Social and Governance (ESG) risks, opportunities =
and issues throughout the research process via [the Sub-Adviser=E2=80=99s] =
proprietary quality reviews, in an effort to ensure that any material ESG i=
ssues are considered.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An=
d when BNY Mellon got requests for proposals from other investment firms, i=
t described the funds as considering ESG stuff:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">During the Relevant Period, BNYMIA prepared RFP Responses =
to other investment firms that were evaluating the Overlay Funds for their =
own clients. In response to numerous inquiries regarding ESG considerations=
, BNYMIA included language that described the Sub-Adviser=E2=80=99s Respons=
ible Investment Team=E2=80=99s research process, including its preparation =
of ESG quality reviews. BNYMIA provided RFP Responses which stated that the=
 Sub-Adviser=E2=80=99s Responsible Investment Team prepared an ESG quality =
review for every security recommended by the Sub-Adviser=E2=80=99s analysts=
. For example, BNYMIA stated in an RFP Response that =E2=80=9CESG considera=
tions are taken into account at every stage of the investment process=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9Cahead of investing, each security being considered for inv=
estment by our global industry analysts must have an ESG quality review con=
ducted by a member of [the Responsible Investment Team].=E2=80=9D</p></bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here there are=C2=A0<em>absolutely no s=
ubstantive claims=C2=A0</em>about <em>how</em> BNY Mellon takes these facto=
rs into account. =E2=80=9CWe review every investment for ESG quality and th=
en buy whichever stocks we think will go up,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhichever=
 stocks have the highest dividend yields,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhichever st=
ocks are in the index,=E2=80=9D would all be consistent with what these sta=
tements actually say. Or =E2=80=9Cbefore we invest, our responsible investm=
ent team writes a report on the stock, which we then throw away before anyo=
ne can read it.=E2=80=9D There is nothing here that gives the SEC a hook to=
 sue BNY Mellon on a theory like =E2=80=9Cyou said you cared about ESG but =
actually you prioritized economics over ESG.=E2=80=9D The only claims here =
are that BNY Mellon <em>considered=C2=A0</em>ESG factors, not that it did a=
nything specific about them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However! Appar=
ently it did not=C2=A0<em>always=C2=A0</em>consider those factors.=C2=A0The=
=C2=A0Overlay Funds would sometimes buy stocks and bonds without an=C2=A0ES=
G review:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Numerous equity and/o=
r corporate bond investments held by certain Overlay Funds did not have an =
ESG quality review score as of the time of investment. For example, out of =
185 investments made by one Overlay Fund between January 1, 2019 and March =
31, 2021, 67 did not have an ESG quality review score as of the time of inv=
estment (or, in the case of corporate bonds, within 30 days after purchase,=
 consistent with the Sub-Adviser=E2=80=99s policy), amounting to nearly 25 =
percent of the fund=E2=80=99s net assets as of March 31, 2021.=C2=A0</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So =E2=80=A6=C2=A0this is BNY Mellon=
 selling=C2=A0<em>non</em>-ESG funds with marketing materials that say =E2=
=80=9Cwe consider ESG for every investment,=E2=80=9D but in fact they only =
considered ESG for like 75% of their investments. They said they always wro=
te reports, but sometimes they did not write reports. Fraud!</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose that this could be the first case in a wave of =
SEC ESG enforcement actions, but I want to emphasize how limited it is, and=
 how inevitable those limits are.=C2=A0<em>In general</em>, the marketing p=
itch for an ESG fund will be[3]:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; =
padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">W=
e consider a range of environmental, social and governance factors that we =
think matter, and balance those factors against each other subjectively to =
produce some sort of explicit or implicit ESG score.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Then we consider the ESG score along with traditional=C2=
=A0research on the stock=E2=80=99s fundamental value, and balance our valua=
tion view with our ESG view to decide what stocks to buy.</li></ol><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you want, you can probably find things to object to=
 in the way any ESG fund does either of these weightings. You can probably =
find some funds that do these weightings in ways that you find outrageous a=
nd cavalier and destructive and even dishonest. But it is hard for the SEC =
to do that without=C2=A0<em>proof=C2=A0</em>that the fund is being=C2=A0<em=
>knowingly=C2=A0</em>dishonest. If a fund writes an ESG report, it=E2=80=99=
s hard for the SEC to say =E2=80=9Cyour ESG report wasn=E2=80=99t good enou=
gh,=E2=80=9D or even =E2=80=9Cyou did not give enough weight to your ESG re=
ports in choosing which stocks to buy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But if it doesn=E2=80=
=99t write the report at all, sure, that=E2=80=99s a problem.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lesson here is that, if you say you have an ESG pr=
ocess for all of your investments, then you have to have an ESG process for=
 all of your investments. There are no lessons about what that process has =
to look like.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"aut=
o" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
