<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Crypto insider trading</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a cryptocurrency insider tradi=
ng scandal that I would like to see:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decim=
al; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">There is some crypto project that does something. People work together t=
o build something that adds value to the world, and there are tokens that r=
epresent some form of economic interest in that project. If the project suc=
ceeds and the underlying product is widely used and beloved, the tokens wil=
l be valuable; if the project fails, the tokens will be worthless.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Something good happens at the project. A t=
rial version of the product works really well, some regulatory approval is =
received, some big business decides to use the project, whatever: Some even=
t occurs that materially increases the probability that the project will su=
cceed and, thus, that the token will be valuable.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">After the event happens, but before it is publicly announce=
d, some insider of the project buys a bunch of tokens.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Then the event is announced publicly, the tokens go up=
, and the insider gets rich from her well-timed token purchases.</li></ol><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is nothing particularly novel or interest=
ing about this; this is just insider trading. Just normal insider trading. =
Happens at companies all the time: A company has good quarterly earnings or=
 a good drug trial or lands a big customer or whatever, an insider buys sto=
ck, the news comes out, the stock goes up, totally normal stuff. Illegal st=
uff! But normal.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the crypto insider=
 trading scandal that I actually see, repeatedly:</p><ol style=3D"list-styl=
e-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">There is some crypto project. Maybe it does something, but =
this is irrelevant to the discussion.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">What is relevant is=C2=A0<em>market depth:=C2=A0</em>If you can sell th=
e project=E2=80=99s token to more people, then it will be more valuable. In=
 particular, if it is listed on one of the big cryptocurrency exchanges, th=
e price will go up, because more people will buy it, independent of any con=
siderations about what the token actually does or whether the project will =
ultimately succeed.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The project=E2=
=80=99s token gets listed on a big exchange.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">While the listing is being considered, but before it is publicly=
 announced, somebody =E2=80=94=C2=A0presumably an insider of the project=C2=
=A0or of the exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0buys a bunch of tokens.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The token lists on the exchange, the price goes =
up, and the insider gets rich from her well-timed token purchases.</li></ol=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a sense this is novel and interesting beca=
use crypto tokens are (at least sometimes) not securities, everything happe=
ns vaguely offshore, and the law of insider trading in this area is underde=
veloped and arguably unclear. It is also interesting because the insider tr=
ading tends to occur on public blockchains, which means (1) everyone can se=
e the concentrated well-timed trades right before the listing event but (2)=
 you can=E2=80=99t necessarily tie the wallet doing those trades to the act=
ual person involved (to see if it=E2=80=99s an insider, etc.). But the insi=
de information is always fundamentally=C2=A0<em>about the exchange</em>, no=
t=C2=A0<em>about the project</em>. The core inside information is never =E2=
=80=9Cthe fundamental value of this token has increased,=E2=80=9D always =
=E2=80=9Cwe can sell this token to more people.=E2=80=9D It is a dispiritin=
g sort of insider trading.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27811549.267618/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3=
NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9jcnlwdG8tbWlnaHQtaGF2ZS1hbi1pbnNpZGVyLXRyYWRpbmctcHJvY=
mxlbS0xMTY1MzA4NDM5OA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e4a1625" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Anyway</a>=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over six days last August, on=
e crypto wallet amassed a stake of $360,000 worth of Gnosis coins, a token =
tied to an effort to build blockchain-based prediction markets. On the seve=
nth day, Binance=E2=80=94the world=E2=80=99s largest cryptocurrency exchang=
e by volume=E2=80=94said in a blog post that it would list Gnosis, allowing=
 it to be traded among its users.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Token lis=
tings add both liquidity and a stamp of legitimacy to the token, and often =
provide a boost to a token=E2=80=99s trading price. The price of Gnosis ros=
e sharply, from around $300 to $410 within an hour. The value of Gnosis tra=
ded that day surged to more than seven times its seven-day average.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Four minutes after Binance=E2=80=99s announcement,=
 the wallet began selling down its stake, liquidating it entirely in just o=
ver four hours for slightly more than $500,000=E2=80=94netting a profit of =
about $140,000 and a return of roughly 40%, according to an analysis perfor=
med by Argus Inc., a firm that offers companies software to manage employee=
 trading. The same wallet demonstrated similar patterns of buying tokens be=
fore their listings and selling quickly after with at least three other tok=
ens.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look, this=C2=A0<em>exist=
s=C2=A0</em>in traditional finance. There was a <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27811549.267618/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDktMjEvcy1wLWluZGV4LW1hbmFnZXItY2hhcmdlZC13=
aXRoLTkwMC0wMDAtaW5zaWRlci10cmFkaW5nLXNjaGVtZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTIzMjJfTU9ORVl=
TVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMj=
A1MjMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1d3fded2" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> fun 2020 case</a> against an S&amp;P Global Inc. manager who alleged=
ly traded on inside information about what stocks would be added to indexes=
; information about liquidity and demand can be material, just like informa=
tion about the actual business. But this is rare;=C2=A0<em>most=C2=A0</em>o=
f the material information about stocks is information about the business. =
In crypto it is the reverse.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=
=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"2">
